{"timestamp": "2025-12-01 16:30:34.146086", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnosis report — network state snapshot\\n\\nTimestamp: (based on provided measurements)\\nScope: full lab topology (hosts, server farm, load balancer, DHCP/DNS, FRR routers, access switches)\\n\\nExecutive summary\\n- Overall the user-facing network is behaving correctly: host_1_1_1_1 and host_2_1_1_1 obtain connectivity to infrastructure (DNS, DHCP) and to the published web service (load_balancer and web_server_{0..3}). Core/distribution OSPF routing is present and converged across router_core_1/2/3 and server_access_router.\\n- There are a number of “unknown”/no-response ICMP results involving the 20.200.0.0/24 addresses (backend_web_*) when probed from many other nodes. This is consistent with an isolated backend network (20.200.0.0/24) that is not advertised/routed into the main fabric; the load balancer is the only 10.200/20.200 peer visible and is reachable from both sides.\\n- No devices appear to be down; key infrastructure (dhcp_server, dns_server, load_balancer, web_server_0..3) respond to pings from hosts and servers. OSPF routes on the four routers examined show normal adjacency and expected learned routes.\\n\\nDetailed findings (evidence + interpretation)\\n\\n1) Reachability summary (from get_reachability)\\n- Hosts (10.1.1.10, 10.2.1.10) -> infrastructure:\\n  - host_1_1_1_1 and host_2_1_1_1 can ping dns_server (10.200.0.2), dhcp_server (10.200.0.8), load_balancer (10.200.0.7) and web_server_0..3 (10.200.0.3..6) with 0% packet loss and modest RTTs (≈2–4 ms). This shows host-plane connectivity to DNS/DHCP/web front-end is healthy.\\n- Hosts -> backend_web_* (20.200.0.x)\\n  - All pings toward backend_web_0/1/2 from the hosts are “unknown” (no TX/RX stats). Pattern: hosts cannot directly ping 20.200.0.x addresses.\\n  - Interpretation: Backend network 20.200.0.0/24 is not directly reachable from host subnets — consistent with intentional isolation of backend servers.\\n- backend_web_* (20.200.0.x) -> load_balancer (10.200.0.7)\\n  - backend_web_0/1/2 can ping load_balancer successfully with low RTT. backend_web nodes can also ping each other. This shows the backend network has connectivity to the load balancer.\\n- backend_web_* -> other 10.200.x infrastructure (dns_server, dhcp_server, web_server_x)\\n  - Many backend_web_* -> dns_server/dhcp_server/web_server_* pings are “unknown” (no response), i.e. backends cannot reach most other 10.200 hosts except load_balancer and other 20.200 nodes.\\n  - Interpretation: 20.200 hosts see the load_balancer but not the rest of the 10.200 subnet. This suggests no general routing/advertisement for 20.200 or that traffic from 20.200 is limited to the load_balancer (or blocked by ACLs/firewall on the servers or router).\\n\\n2) FRR routing (frr_show_ip_route outputs for router_core_1, router_core_2, router_core_3, server_access_router)\\n- server_access_router:\\n  - 10.200.0.0/24 is directly connected (br0). 10.1.1.0/24 and 10.2.1.0/24 are learned and point via 172.16.0.10 (eth7).\\n  - No route entry for 20.200.0.0/24 is present in the server_access_router routing output.\\n- router_core_1/2/3:\\n  - All show learned OSPF routes for the 10.* host subnets and for 10.200.0.0/24 via different next-hops (multi-paths/expected).\\n  - No advertisement or learned route for 20.200.0.0/24 in the core routers’ outputs.\\n- Interpretation:\\n  - 20.200.0.0/24 is not being advertised into OSPF and is not present in the routers’ routing tables. The only device(s) that appear to be on 20.200 are the backend_web_* and (likely) an interface on the load_balancer. This matches the reachability pattern where only the load_balancer (10.200.0.7) communicates with 20.200 hosts.\\n\\nAnomalies / deviations from “flat” connectivity\\n- Large set of “unknown” ICMP results for pairs involving 20.200.0.0/24:\\n  - host_* -> backend_web_* = unknown (expected by design: backend network is isolated)\\n  - backend_web_* -> web_server_* (10.200) and backend_web_* -> dns/dhcp = unknown (not strictly expected if backend servers require access to DNS/DHCP; but may be intentional)\\n- One elevated jitter observation:\\n  - web_server_3 -> load_balancer RTT shows higher variance (max 14.495 ms, mdev 5.687) compared to other server pairs (typical mdev ~0.3–0.7 ms). However the average RTT remains small and loss = 0%. This is an isolated jitter/spike observation only for that pair during the measurement window.\\n\\nLocalization of observed behavior\\n- Backend isolation: problem area = 20.200.0.0/24 (backend network). Devices implicated:\\n  - backend_web_0/1/2 (20.200.0.x) — these hosts are on an isolated subnet.\\n  - load_balancer (10.200.0.7) — appears to be the bridging/peering point between 20.200 and 10.200 and is reachable from both sides.\\n  - server_access_router / FRR core routers — do not have any route for 20.200.0.0/24 (20.200 is not in OSPF/RIB). The server_access_router shows only 10.200 connected.\\n- Jitter spike:\\n  - web_server_3 <-> load_balancer observed jitter; localized to that server pair for the measurement interval. Could be transient or related to host-level scheduling or brief load.\\n\\nProbable root cause(s) (based on the evidence)\\n- Backend network (20.200.0.0/24) is intentionally or unintentionally isolated from the routed fabric:\\n  - Root cause A (most likely / design): The backend network is not connected to the FRR routers and therefore is not advertised in OSPF. The load_balancer has connectivity to both networks and provides the only path between the backend and the rest of the network; that explains:\\n    - hosts cannot ping backend_web_* (no route towards 20.200 via routers),\\n    - backend_web_* can reach the load_balancer (local path) but cannot reach other 10.200 nodes (no routing path or return path from them to 20.200).\\n  - Root cause B (alternate/complementary): There may be access control (ACLs or host firewalls) preventing direct ICMP/communication between 20.200 hosts and other 10.200 hosts except the load_balancer. The behavior is consistent with restrictive policies.\\n- OSPF and router plane: No OSPF/adjacency issues observed between the core/distribution/server_access routers; routes to expected subnets are present and converged. No evidence of a routing loop or missing core connectivity.\\n- The isolated ping failures are not symptomatic of router failures or OSPF instability — rather they are caused by network design (no L3 gateway for 20.200 advertised) or intentional isolation/filtering.\\n\\nOther observations\\n- All user-facing services (DNS, DHCP, web front-end via load_balancer) are reachable from hosts with 0% loss during the tests — service plane is healthy.\\n- Load balancer reachability:\\n  - load_balancer is reachable from hosts and from backend nodes; backends can reach it; this is consistent with its role.\\n- OSPF metrics differ per route (varied costs across cores); this is normal for multi-core topology and equal-cost or unequal-cost multipath routing seen in outputs.\\n\\nSummary / conclusion\\n- Network core and distribution OSPF routing is healthy and converged; host subnets can reach DNS, DHCP and the published web service (load_balancer and web_server_0..3).\\n- The primary “anomaly” is intentional-looking isolation of the backend network 20.200.0.0/24:\\n  - 20.200 nodes are not present in router OSPF routes and are unreachable from hosts and most 10.200 servers, except for the load_balancer which is reachable from both sides.\\n  - This behavior aligns with the stated design goal that backend web servers should not be directly accessible from hosts. If additional connectivity (e.g., for backend servers to reach DNS/DHCP or management systems) is expected, this isolation explains the lack of reachability.\\n- No failing routers or device-level down events were detected; no packet loss observed toward critical services in the tested window.\\n\\nIf you want, I can:\\n- Enumerate exactly which node-to-node pings are “unknown” (list), or\\n- Pull FRR OSPF configuration/LSDB and the load_balancer network interfaces, or\\n- Test HTTP/port-level connectivity to verify load balancer behavior.\\n\\n(Per instruction I have not proposed mitigations — above is diagnosis and localization of anomalies and probable root causes.), please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='c914a290-0523-402b-a817-3a63c2c36a8a'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
